	<entry>
		<title>Debugger</title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.messylab.com/component/content/article/6-front-page/5-debugger"/>
		<published>2010-07-26T16:51:25Z</published>
		<updated>2010-07-26T16:51:25Z</updated>
		<id>http://www.messylab.com/component/content/article/6-front-page/5-debugger</id>
		<author>
			<name>Miloš Anđelković</name>
		<email>drstorm@messylab.com</email>
		</author>
		<summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Messy Lab comes with its own debugger. It is well integrated within the environment, but it can be used as a stand-alone command-line (CLI) application as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The CLI flont-end uses commands similar to those of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gnu.org/software/gdb/&quot;&gt;GDB&lt;/a&gt;, so anyone familiar with GDB should feel right at home.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, with the support of the underlying execution environment, e.g. a virtual machine, the debugger features historical, or backwards execution.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
		<content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Messy Lab comes with its own debugger. It is well integrated within the environment, but it can be used as a stand-alone command-line (CLI) application as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The CLI flont-end uses commands similar to those of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gnu.org/software/gdb/&quot;&gt;GDB&lt;/a&gt;, so anyone familiar with GDB should feel right at home.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, with the support of the underlying execution environment, e.g. a virtual machine, the debugger features historical, or backwards execution.&lt;/p&gt;</content>
	</entry>
